---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const seo = {
  title: "Tax Loss Harvesting Strategies in the US (2026 Guide)",
  description: "Learn how to use tax loss harvesting to offset capital gains and up to $3,000 of ordinary income. Master the IRS wash-sale rule and boost your portfolio's after-tax return.",
  schema: `
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
      {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Article",
        "headline": "Tax Loss Harvesting Strategies in the US",
        "author": {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Mrittunjoy Das"
        },
        "publisher": {
          "@type": "Organization",
          "name": "TaxDebtWealthSuite"
        },
        "datePublished": "2026-07-22",
        "dateModified": "2026-07-23",
        "description": "Learn how to use tax loss harvesting to offset capital gains and up to $3,000 of ordinary income."
      }
    </script>
    <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
      {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is the IRS wash-sale rule?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The wash-sale rule prohibits you from claiming a capital loss on a security if you buy a 'substantially identical' security within 30 days before or after the sale. If triggered, the loss is disallowed and added to the cost basis of the new purchase."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How much ordinary income can I offset with capital losses?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "In the US, after your capital losses have offset your capital gains, you can use up to $3,000 of net capital loss per year to offset your ordinary income ($1,500 if married filing separately)."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Do capital losses expire?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "No. If your net capital losses exceed the $3,000 annual limit for offsetting ordinary income, the remaining balance can be carried forward indefinitely into future tax years."
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    </script>
  `
};
---

<Layout title={seo.title} description={seo.description} head={seo.schema}>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
    <header class="mb-12 text-center">
      <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1 rounded-full bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest border border-emerald-500/20 mb-6">
        <span>US Tax Strategy</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight mb-6 leading-tight">
        Tax Loss Harvesting Strategies in the US
      </h1>
      <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-4 text-sm text-slate-400">
        <span class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <img src="https://ui-avatars.com/api/?name=Mrittunjoy+Das&background=00F5D4&color=000" alt="Mrittunjoy Das" class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full" />
          By <span class="text-white font-medium">Mrittunjoy Das</span>
        </span>
        <span>•</span>
        <time datetime="2026-07-22">July 22, 2026</time>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- Embedded Calculator Callout Banner -->
    <div class="my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-r from-[#141C32] to-[#1E294B] border border-[#00F5D4]/30 flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center justify-between gap-6">
      <div class="space-y-1">
        <span class="text-xs font-bold text-[#00F5D4] uppercase tracking-wider">Interactive Tool</span>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white">US Tax Loss Harvesting Calculator</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-slate-300">Calculate exactly how much you can save by offsetting your specific gains and up to $3,000 of ordinary income.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/tax-loss-harvesting-calculator/" class="px-5 py-2.5 rounded-xl bg-[#00F5D4] hover:bg-[#00F5D4]/90 text-slate-950 font-bold text-xs whitespace-nowrap transition-all shadow-lg shadow-[#00F5D4]/20">
        Calculate Tax Savings →
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-8 text-slate-300 text-base leading-relaxed">
      <section class="glass-panel p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">Introduction</h2>
        <p>
          Nobody likes losing money in the stock market. However, when the market takes a dip, savvy investors look for the silver lining: <strong>Tax Loss Harvesting</strong>. By strategically selling losing investments, you can offset the taxes owed on your winning investments and even reduce your taxable ordinary income.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="glass-panel p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">The Mechanics of Tax Loss Harvesting</h2>
        <p>
          Tax loss harvesting is a technique used to lower your taxes by selling an investment that has lost value and replacing it with a similar—but not identical—investment to maintain your portfolio's target asset allocation. The realized loss is then used to offset capital gains or ordinary income.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mt-4">Step 1: Netting Short-Term and Long-Term</h3>
        <p>
          Under IRS rules, capital gains and losses are categorized as either short-term (held for one year or less) or long-term (held for more than one year). When you harvest a loss, it must first be used to offset gains of the same type. If you have excess losses in one category, they can then be applied against gains in the other category.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mt-4">Step 2: Offsetting Ordinary Income</h3>
        <p>
          If your total capital losses exceed your total capital gains for the year, you can use up to <strong>$3,000 of the net capital loss to offset your ordinary income</strong> (such as your salary or W-2 wages). If you are married filing separately, this limit is $1,500. This is one of the most powerful aspects of tax loss harvesting, as it directly reduces your income tax liability at your highest marginal tax rate.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="glass-panel p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">The IRS Wash-Sale Rule</h2>
        <p>
          The biggest pitfall in tax loss harvesting is the <strong>Wash-Sale Rule</strong>. To prevent investors from creating artificial losses just for tax benefits, the IRS prohibits you from claiming a loss if you purchase a "substantially identical" security within 30 days before or after the sale.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you trigger a wash sale, the loss is disallowed. Instead, the disallowed loss is added to the cost basis of the newly purchased asset, meaning you will eventually get the tax benefit when you sell the new asset, but you cannot claim the loss in the current tax year.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mt-4">How to Avoid Wash Sales</h3>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Wait 31 Days:</strong> The simplest method is to sell the losing asset, keep the cash on the sidelines for 31 days, and then buy it back. However, this exposes you to "cash drag" if the market rebounds during that month.</li>
          <li><strong>Buy a Proxy ETF:</strong> Sell your losing S&P 500 ETF and immediately buy a Russell 1000 ETF. Because they track different indices, they are not considered substantially identical.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch Your IRA:</strong> The wash-sale rule applies across all your accounts, including IRAs. If you sell a stock at a loss in your taxable brokerage account and buy the same stock in your IRA within 30 days, the loss is permanently disallowed.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="glass-panel p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">Carrying Forward Losses</h2>
        <p>
          If you have a massive market crash and harvest $50,000 in losses, you obviously cannot deduct that entire amount against ordinary income in a single year due to the $3,000 limit. However, the IRS allows you to <strong>carry forward the remaining $47,000 indefinitely</strong> into future tax years.
        </p>
        <p>
          In subsequent years, this carryover loss will automatically offset any new capital gains you generate, and if there are still losses remaining, it will offset another $3,000 of ordinary income each year until the balance is exhausted.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="glass-panel p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-800 space-y-4">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">Advanced Strategies</h2>
        <p>
          While tax loss harvesting is primarily a defensive strategy, it pairs incredibly well with offensive tax planning. If you have significant carried forward losses, you can strategically pair them with:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Roth Conversions:</strong> While capital losses don't offset the ordinary income generated by a <a href="/roth-conversion-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Roth Conversion</a> beyond the $3,000 limit, lowering your overall AGI can keep you in a lower tax bracket.</li>
          <li><strong>Portfolio Rebalancing:</strong> Use harvested losses to offset the gains incurred when you sell highly appreciated assets to rebalance your portfolio back to its target asset allocation.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoiding the NIIT:</strong> By aggressively offsetting capital gains, high earners can keep their Net Investment Income below the threshold for the 3.8% Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT). (See our <a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Capital Gains Tax Calculator</a>).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Remember, the goal of investing is to make money, not to lose it just for a tax deduction. However, in volatile markets, tax loss harvesting is one of the few guaranteed ways to generate alpha and improve your long-term, after-tax returns.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Methodology -->
      <section class="p-6 rounded-2xl bg-slate-900 border border-slate-800 space-y-3 text-xs text-slate-300">
        <h4 class="text-sm font-bold text-white">Methodology & IRS Source References</h4>
        <p>Calculations adhere to IRS Code Section 1211 (capital loss limitations), IRS Code Section 1091 (wash-sale rules), and IRS Publication 550 (Investment Income and Expenses).</p>
        <p><strong>Official Reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p550" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">IRS Publication 550 (Investment Income & Expenses)</a></p>
      </section>

      <!-- Related Calculators Grid -->
      <section class="space-y-4 pt-4">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white border-b border-slate-800 pb-3">Related Calculators & Tools</h3>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <a href="/tax-loss-harvesting-calculator/" class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-slate-900 border border-slate-800 hover:border-[#00F5D4]/40 transition-all space-y-2">
            <span class="text-xs font-bold text-[#00F5D4] uppercase">Calculator</span>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-bold text-white">Tax Loss Harvesting Tool</h4>
            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">Offset gains & ordinary income with losses.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/" class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-slate-900 border border-slate-800 hover:border-indigo-500/40 transition-all space-y-2">
            <span class="text-xs font-bold text-indigo-400 uppercase">Related Tool</span>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-bold text-white">Capital Gains Tax Calculator</h4>
            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">Estimate short & long term CGT liabilities.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/" class="p-4 rounded-xl bg-slate-900 border border-slate-800 hover:border-amber-500/40 transition-all space-y-2">
            <span class="text-xs font-bold text-amber-400 uppercase">Related Tool</span>
            <h4 class="text-sm font-bold text-white">Buy, Borrow, Die Calculator</h4>
            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">Avoid capital gains taxes via SBLOCs.</p>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
